                /            \
            monkey (2)        lion (5)
            /    \            /   \
           /      \          /     \
     grass (3)  fruit (4) zebra (6) giraffe (7)
     
Numbers in parentheses show visit order


C) POST-ORDER TRAVERSAL

Rule: Left → Right → Root

Algorithm for Post-order Traversal:

Algorithm: PostOrderTraversal(node)
Input: Root node of tree (or subtree)

Step 1: If the node is NULL, return
Step 2: Recursively traverse the LEFT subtree (PostOrderTraversal(node.Left))
Step 3: Recursively traverse the RIGHT subtree (PostOrderTraversal(node.Right))
Step 4: VISIT the current node (process node data)
Step 5: End


Step-by-Step Post-order Traversal:

Step 1: Start at root (Vulture) → go left to monkey
Step 2: At monkey → go left to grass
Step 3: At grass → left and right are NULL, so VISIT grass
        ✓ VISITED: grass
        
Step 4: Back to monkey → go right to fruit
Step 5: At fruit → left and right are NULL, so VISIT fruit
        ✓ VISITED: grass, fruit
        
Step 6: Back to monkey → both left and right done, so VISIT monkey
        ✓ VISITED: grass, fruit, monkey
        
Step 7: Back to Vulture → go right to lion
Step 8: At lion → go left to zebra
Step 9: At zebra → left and right are NULL, so VISIT zebra
        ✓ VISITED: grass, fruit, monkey, zebra
        
Step 10: Back to lion → go right to giraffe
Step 11: At giraffe → left and right are NULL, so VISIT giraffe
        ✓ VISITED: grass, fruit, monkey, zebra, giraffe
        
Step 12: Back to lion → both left and right done, so VISIT lion
        ✓ VISITED: grass, fruit, monkey, zebra, giraffe, lion
        
Step 13: Back to Vulture → both left and right done, so VISIT Vulture
        ✓ VISITED: grass, fruit, monkey, zebra, giraffe, lion, Vulture


Post-order Traversal Result:

grass → fruit → monkey → zebra → giraffe → lion → Vulture


Post-order Traversal Path Diagram:

                    Vulture (7)
